## Thread.Abort Migration â€” `EventProcessor`

### Inventory

| Line | API | Purpose |
|------|-----|---------|
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Interrupt()` | Wake thread from `WaitOne()` |
| `Stop()` | `Thread.Abort()` | Force-kill thread after timeout |
| `RunLoop()` | `while (true)` | Unbounded loop â€” no cooperative exit |

Both `Thread.Abort()` (throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`) and `Thread.Interrupt()` (`SYSLIB0046`) are broken/obsolete in modern .NET.

### Pattern Classification

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `RunLoop()` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| Blocking call interruption | `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| Timeout enforcement | `Thread.Abort` fallback | `CancellationToken` â€” cooperative exit handles this |

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var waitHandles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either a new event arrives OR cancellation is requested
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(waitHandles);

            if (signaled == 1) // token.WaitHandle fired â€” shutting down
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals token.WaitHandle, waking the thread
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for cooperative exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop must cooperatively check for shutdown |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(waitHandles)` | Wakes on **either** new work or cancellation â€” no `Interrupt` needed |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Token's `WaitHandle` becomes signaled, unblocking `WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Cooperative exit via token makes force-kill unnecessary |
| Single `Dequeue` per signal | Drain loop | Fixes a pre-existing race: rapid `Enqueue` calls could lose signals |

### Key Pitfalls to Avoid

1. **Don't replace `WaitOne()` with just a token check** â€” the thread must *wake up* when cancelled. `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` solves this. A bare `token.IsCancellationRequested` after `WaitOne()` never runs because `WaitOne()` blocks forever.

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** â€” it leaks internal timer/callback resources. Implement `IDisposable` on the owning class.

3. **Don't assume cancellation is instant** â€” if `Handle(item)` takes a long time, the thread won't check the token until it finishes. Pass the token into `Handle()` too if it does significant work.

4. **The original code had a bug** â€” `ManualResetEvent` is binary; two rapid `Enqueue` calls produce two `Set()` calls but only one `WaitOne()` unblock. The migrated version drains the full queue each time to fix this.

### Even More Idiomatic: `Channel<T>`

For new .NET 8 code, consider replacing the entire manual threading with `Channel<T>`:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start() =>
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            Handle(item);
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) =>
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        if (_runTask is not null)
            await _runTask.ConfigureAwait(false);
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();
    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

This eliminates all manual locking, `WaitHandle` management, and threading concerns. `Channel<T>` handles backpressure, thread-safe queueing, and cancellation natively.
